<img
src='http://www.advfn.com/p.php?pid=financialgraphs&title=5YR+Trend+Bookvalue+P
%2C+Cap+Invested+PS&a0=10.95&a1=7.53&a2=7.41&a3=5.74&a4=4.60&b0=16.9832647585&b
=12.5043640863&b2=10.840226343&b3=8.51773315206&b4=6.74329684084&a_title=Bookva
ue+PS&b_title=Cap+Invested+PS&cache_name=financialsusDNRI5'>

Here DNR has grown their BV each year for the last 5 years as well as continued
their sizable capital investments each year.

--------------------------------------------------------

I recall looking at this site years ago but it was not one that I frequented.
Since I am now focused on calculating Graham Numbers, the 5yr BV and 5yr
earnings statistics really help to smooth out the variance and/or unusual
"one-time" anomalies in candidate company numbers.

When I see 5 yr BV growing (as well as growing capital investments) and 5 yr
earnings growing, its another plus for me buying the stock. This is even more
important now when measured from the 2009 "crash". Companies that have been
able to maintain this growth should even be stronger as the recovery continues.

ADVFN is now bookmarked and next to my Yahoo Finance tab.

Thanks

