Date:1/27/2012 12:00:58 AM
From:Spekulatius
re RFE.AX - as a general rule, I avoid investing in upstart/small companies
that don't list in their home markets. I don't think it makes too much sense to
list in Australia and raise money there, while operating a upstart E&P in the
US. What's the reason - collecting frequent flyer miles, evade taxes, avoid the
SEC scrutiny or just screw unsuspecting investors far away from home, so you
don't crap you nest if things go wrong? Neither explanation appeals to me but
some are definitely worse than others.
%EOM----------------------

%BOM---------------------
Date:1/27/2012 1:14:44 AM
From:Paul Senior
I have money in several stocks of small companies that list in home market &
raise money in home market, but have operations elsewhere. That would be some
Canadian with their business interests elsewhere, Australian with their
business elsewhere, and English also. Doesn't seem to be an issue for me except
when some Aussie companies have issued new stock at below market price, and
they've made that offer only available to Australian citizens (Australian
stockholders).

Although your point is to "upstart/small companies", the US does have history
with these type of investments with larger companies. Dutch East India company
for example. And start-ups: 19th century USA eastern interests ("robber
barons") issuing stock to finance operations in USA western territories to open
mines, build railroads.
%EOM----------------------

%BOM---------------------
Date:1/27/2012 1:44:56 AM
From:Spekulatius
Well, I think in some cases there are legit reasons to raise money in one
market/country A, and start operations in market/country B. One example would
be when country B does not have well established capital & stock markets. That
is a reason why a company that start up ops in let's say Bolivia are listed in
the USA or Canada.
That may be understandable. But why would a company list in Australia, and
operate an upstart E&P in the US? The US has well established capital market,
and deep pool of investors that may invest in E&P ,so I cannot think of a
reason to do it that way that is positive for the respective investors.
