Date:1/28/2012 2:07:12 PM
From:Difco
I feel most of us on this board like Volkswagen (FRA:VOW). A lot of you know
much more than I do about it and I just wanted to mention a couple of things
that interested me. Since 2008 I’ve been following events surrounding the
company and created a folder with paper clippings to keep track.

First, the beginning… Ferdinand Porsche found the Porsche design bureau in 1931
and was the original designer of the VW Beetle. He had two children, Ferdinand
Anton Ernst 'Ferry' Porsche, who held the helm of the new VW Company and his
daughter Louise Hedwig Anna Wilhelmine Maria Piech focused on the Porsche
Holding group. They each had 4 children, but only two of them continued the
family business: Wolfgang Heinz Porsche became the Chairman of Porsche (he's
the son of Ferdinand) and Ferdinand Piech became the Chairman of VW (he's the
son of Louise). Well, I guess the cousins didn't like each other too much, but
they sure liked each other's "das auto". So a few years back the far smaller
Porsche decided to use cash settled options (the banks effectively owned the
shares) to build a majority stake in VW. All of a sudden, in October of 2008,
Porsche disclosed that it holds enough options to purchase 70% of VW. (FT May
26, 2009 – Article called “Collision course) This resulted in a short-squeeze
of the short sellers of VW shares, who scrambled to cover their short positions
(one of them was actually short-champion and a personal hero, Greenlight
Capital). As a result of all this the VLKAY ADR price hit an all time high of
$122 (the ordinary VOW shares on the Frankfurt stock exchange actually traded
for a brief moment for 1,005 euros a share). Everything was well thought out
except for the fact that to purchase the shares, Porsche needed cash that banks
were not lending at that point in time due to the financial crisis. Soon the
options started to expire and Porsche was booking losses on these options.
Ironically, the only way to save Porsche was to have VW buy it, which it
partially did in the fall of 2009 and with the clear goal to become the number
one auto manufacturer in the world. So, VW bought 49.9% share in Porsche’s auto
business for 3.9 billion euros and received a call option for the remaining
50.1% (on the other hand Porsche received a put option for that same amount). A
caveat is that the options can’t be exercised until Nov. 15, 2012 or VW would
be on the hook for approx. 1.3 billion euros. But on the other hand, if the
carmaker waits until the second half of 2014, taxes on exercising the options
would shrink to zero.
(http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-22/volkswagen-says-process-still-ongoing
with-porsche-integration-decision.html). Finally, all the original short
sellers of Volkswagen are suing Porsche for about $1 billion for market
manipulation.

Usually short sellers don’t have faces, but in this story there is one – Adolf
Merckle. Merckle was a German billionaire, who was born in Eastern Germany, but
subsequently moved to the West and built an empire, which spanned from
pharmaceuticals to construction. At one point Merckle had an estimated worth of
over $9 billion. When everything is going your way for such a long time, you
sometimes get a crazy idea to push your luck – in this case Merckle decided to
make a big short bet on Volkwagen. This story has a tragic end, Merckle was
financially ruined and in January of 2009 committed a suicide. His body was
found on the train tracks near his house.
(http://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/07/business/worldbusiness/07merckle.html).

I feel this story reads like a Shakespearean play – family splits, envy between
family members, sabotage, revenge and death. Whenever Volkswagen reaches
selling point, it will be hard to part with it.
