Date:1/31/2012 6:42:24 PM
From:Paul Senior
KRA. I want to point out again where I believe use of the Graham number
overlooks a criterion:

Intelligent Investor ('73 edit.) , p. 182: "Price no more than 15 times
<u>average earnings of the past three years</u>"

KRA's been a volatile performer in terms of earnings. The past three years were
$3.50, 3.07, -.01

Plugging that average number into the equation results in a fair value number
close to current price.

If the argument is that earnings have improved and will continue to improve
given management's recent actions, that's well and good. That though for the
investor would be anticipating future good results on some basis different from
what I believe was Dr. Graham's intent with his number -- to use only
historical data to discern a value opportunity.

-------
Fyi, Kraton's been a pick by richardred who follows several chemical companies
at his thread "Speculating in Takeover Targets"
%EOM----------------------

